data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which **work identically in .NET 8** and require no migration.

That said, the code could be modernized to use `Task`/`Parallel` instead of raw threads:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**No Thread.Abort migration needed here.** If you have other code that *does* call `Thread.Abort`, I can help migrate that to cooperative cancellation with `CancellationToken`.
